body:
this would solve part of the problem, but likely not all of it.  and, lets say a user calls in to get help from an admin - and their directory structure has been customized by them, but now they don't remember what they did because after 6 months, we all forget stuff. how do they get support from it now about the folders? which folder is what? this would be a complete nightmare in terms of supportability, because every user's tree could be different than the reference tree.

the issue in this issue is, i think, an ask for non-inherited folder permissions. there is a growing list of users asking for more complex (non-inherited) permissions that can differ up and down the file tree. the issue is balancing that against the wish for simplicity and ease of use.  permissions can make it much more complicated and harder to use. combine this with the ask for user level permissions (some users are always read only) it begs a design discussion across the board. 

@jancborchardt i remember a design forward thread on this and related topics, is it still out there?
